Data Cleaning¶

Null values in Age, Embarked, Fare, and Cabin
For Age we fill the null values with the median amount
For Embarked we fill the null values with the mode amount
For Fare we fill the null values with the median amount
Drop the Cabin column since it has many null values and can't be replaced, therefore we won't use it
In [10]:

Visualizing Survivors Per Category¶

What did we learn from these plots
Females are more likley to survive than Males
Passengers in 1st clas are more likley to survive than other classes
Passengers in 3rd class are more likely to die than other classes
Passengers that boarded with 2 or more siblings/spouses more likey survived 
Passengers that boarded with no siblings/spouses more likey died
Passengers that boarded with 2 or more parents/children more likey survived 
Passengers that boarded with no parents/children likey died
Passengers that boarded from embarkment C more likely survived than S and Q

Setting Up Data for Modelling by Binning and Dropping¶

In [18]:
#combine traina nd test dataset to make changes to both at the same time
combdata = [train, test]
#currently Sex is male and female, we want to change that to 1 and 0. So we use binning to make male:0 and female:1
binsex = {"male": 0, "female": 1}
#Use for loop to make the binning changes in both datasets
for dataset in combdata:
    dataset['Sex'] = dataset['Sex'].map(binsex)

#currently Embark is S/C/Q, we want to change that to 0,1,2. So we use binning to make S:0, C:1, and Q:2 
binembark = {"S": 0, "C": 1, "Q": 2}
for dataset in combdata:
#Use for loop to make the binning changes in both datasets
    dataset['Embarked'] = dataset['Embarked'].map(binembark)

#Currently we have Parch and SibSp to indicate is person has parent/spouse/sibiling 
#so instead of having both, we can combine them to make 1 column to indicate a person has a family or not
#we set new column Family to Parent + Spouse/sibling
train['Family'] =  train["Parch"] + train["SibSp"]
#if family is greater that 0 then it will be set to 1
train['Family'].loc[train['Family'] > 0] = 1
#if family is less than 0 then it will be set to 0
train['Family'].loc[train['Family'] == 0] = 0
#we do the same thing to the test dataset
test['Family'] =  test["Parch"] + test["SibSp"]
test['Family'].loc[test['Family'] > 0] = 1
test['Family'].loc[test['Family'] == 0] = 0

#To simplify the data for Fare, we look at the line graph
#We see that there is a massive spike on the cheap tickets to death ratio
#this ends at around the 16 mark
#therefore we make fare groups and seperate them
#we use a for loop to set grouped values in both datasets
for dataset in combdata:
    #starting at anyone that is less than or equal to fare 16 is set to 0
    dataset.loc[ dataset['Fare'] <= 16, 'Fare'] = 0,
    #then anyone who is greater than 16 to less than or equal to 35 is set to 1
    dataset.loc[(dataset['Fare'] > 16) & (dataset['Fare'] <= 35), 'Fare'] = 1,
    #then anyone who is greater than 35 to less than or equal to 160 is set to 2
    dataset.loc[(dataset['Fare'] > 35) & (dataset['Fare'] <= 160), 'Fare'] = 2,
    #then anyone who is greater than 160 is set to 3
    dataset.loc[ dataset['Fare'] > 160, 'Fare'] = 3

#To simplify the data for Age, we look at the line graph
#We see that deaths start outnumbring survives at around the age of 16
#therefore we make age groups and seperate them
#we use a for loop to set grouped values in both datasets
for dataset in combdata:
    #starting at anyone that is less than or equal to age 16 is set to 0
    dataset.loc[ dataset['Age'] <= 16, 'Age'] = 0,
    #then anyone who is greater than 16 to less than or equal to 30 is set to 1
    dataset.loc[(dataset['Age'] > 16) & (dataset['Age'] <= 30), 'Age'] = 1,
    #then anyone who is greater than 30 to less than or equal to 40 is set to 2
    dataset.loc[(dataset['Age'] > 30) & (dataset['Age'] <= 40), 'Age'] = 2,
    #then anyone who is greater than 40 to less than or equal to 65 is set to 3
    dataset.loc[(dataset['Age'] > 40) & (dataset['Age'] <= 65), 'Age'] = 3,
    #then anyone who is greater than 65 is set to 4
    dataset.loc[ dataset['Age'] > 65, 'Age'] = 4

Modelling¶

Why perform cross validation?
Instead of just running one time over the data
it is running multiple times over different versions of the data
so you get different percentages depending how many folds are set
So there are multiple ways of looking at the data
We see that the accuracy of the cross validation is lower that the one run accuracy
In [28]:
#Reference:
#https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/classes.html#module-sklearn.metrics
#https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.model_selection.cross_val_predict.html
#https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.metrics.accuracy_score.html
#This function takes a type of algorithm, dataset, label, cross validation amount   
def train_algo(algo, X_train,Y_train, cv):
    #create the model and fit algorithm to data and label
    model = algo.fit(X_train, Y_train)
    #Set accuracy score
    accuracy = round(model.score(X_train, Y_train)*100, 2)
    #Perform Cross Validation to function with number of jobs
    prediction = model_selection.cross_val_predict(algo, X_train, Y_train, cv=cv, n_jobs = -1)
    #Cross validation score on the label and prediction model
    cv_score = round(metrics.accuracy_score(Y_train, prediction) * 100, 2)
    #finally it will returnt he predictions, accuracy, and cross validation score 
    return prediction, accuracy, cv_score
